The main scientific outcomes of the project established a collection of rigorous connections between the discrete geometry of large networks and the continuous geometry of their latent spaces. Specific classes of results include:

the first proofs demonstrating the convergence of curvature of random geometric graphs to the curvature of the smooth spaces underlying them;
the identification of general conditions under which random graphs in latent spaces exhibit structural properties commonly observed in real-world networks;
the derivation of formulas for computing distances in various smooth spaces, both Riemannian and Lorentzian, and the construction of methods to estimate these distances based on the structure of random graphs built upon these spaces;
one of the earliest applications of machine learning to learning certain properties of spaces in string theory;
the first proofs of the unbiasedness ("maximal randomness") of a class of network models with power-law degree distributions; and
the first rigorous treatment of power laws in real-world networks using extreme value theory.



On the application side, the project developed new tools, the most accurate to date, to embed real-world networks into their latent spaces. The application of these tools to link prediction significantly improved its accuracy, outperforming all existing methods in predicting links that are the hardest to predict. Another major outcome of the project on the application side was a patent for geometric routing in content-centric networks.


Overall, the project resulted in approximately 40 interdisciplinary publications spanning network science, physics, mathematics, and computer science. Two reviews were published: one on network geometry in Nature Reviews, and another on random simplicial complexes in a book chapter. A host of software packages and datasets were released for public use. The project participants organized seven interdisciplinary workshops. The project provided training for three postdoctoral researchers, three graduate students, and three undergraduate students, most of whom have progressed up to prestigious and highly competitive positions in their academic careers.


Finally, the project opened new research avenues, particularly in unlabeled networks, the limits of sparse networks, and the application of network science to machine learning.					Last Modified: 12/01/2024

